&quot;There is no apostrophe in the town name, Buzzards Bay.&quot;
Similar confusion with a town in Ontario, which has 3 variants:
 &quot;Smith's Falls&quot; or &quot;Smith Falls&quot; or  &quot;Smiths Falls&quot;

It's almost impossible to say &quot;Smiths Falls.&quot; It comes out as &quot;Smiss Falls&quot;
Nice bascule bridge there, btw. (Scherzer rolling lift bridge, 1913)

[http://www.flickr.com/photos/drummondwilson/4003460084/]

@ Jim Rees &mdash; 
No doubt about your research!  &nbsp;As explained by the Library of Congress in the Notes (above): <i>&quot;Title [of the photo is] from unverified data provided by the Bain News Service on the negatives ...&quot;</i>  &nbsp;At the time of this photograph (c.1910) the conventional spelling was <i>Buzzard's Bay</i>, which is what Bain News would have used. The Post Office maintains its own style guide.
&nbsp;

@ technogeo &mdash; Could be!  I have no idea ;-)&nbsp;  If you click on the reference link &quot;2&quot; that follows that statement, you can read the original source &mdash; it's in the first paragraph &mdash;  but it doesn't really hint at the reason.  Maybe because it was a double track bridge, it anticipated the weight of two steam engines at the same time ?

The end of that article says the (newer) bridge is used today almost exclusively by trash trains!
&nbsp;
